Lab 05 - URL-Based Access Control Can Be Circumvented
Objective
Access the administrator panel by bypassing URL-based access control and delete the user carlos.

Background
Many web applications place a Reverse Proxy (such as Nginx, Apache, IIS, or a Load Balancer) in front of the backend application.

The reverse proxy often performs access control by checking the requested URL before forwarding the request to the backend server.

Example:

Browser
    │
    ▼
Reverse Proxy
    │
Checks URL
    │
    ▼
Backend Application
Normally, if a user requests:

GET /admin
the reverse proxy blocks the request and returns:

403 Forbidden
without forwarding the request to the backend.

However, some backend frameworks support special HTTP headers such as:

X-Original-URL
X-Rewrite-URL
These headers were originally designed for URL rewriting between reverse proxies and backend servers.

If the reverse proxy checks only the requested URL while the backend trusts these headers, both components interpret the request differently, leading to an Access Control Bypass.

Vulnerability
Broken Access Control due to Platform Misconfiguration

The reverse proxy enforced access control based only on the requested URL.

The backend application trusted the user-controlled X-Original-URL header.

An attacker could manipulate this header to access protected administrator functionality.

Initial Observation
Direct access to:

/admin
returned

403 Forbidden
indicating that access control was implemented at the front-end proxy.

Methodology
Step 1 – Test Direct Access
Requested:

GET /admin HTTP/2
Response:

403 Forbidden
This confirmed that the administrator endpoint existed but was protected.

Step 2 – Investigate Platform Behaviour
Since the lab title mentioned URL-based access control, the possibility of URL rewriting was investigated.

Common rewrite headers include:

X-Original-URL
X-Rewrite-URL
Step 3 – Modify the Request
Instead of requesting:

GET /admin HTTP/2
the following request was sent:

GET / HTTP/2
Host: vulnerable-site
Cookie: session=...

X-Original-URL: /admin
The reverse proxy examined only:

GET /
and therefore allowed the request.

The backend trusted:

X-Original-URL: /admin
and returned the administrator panel.

Step 4 – Delete Carlos
The delete endpoint was identified from the administrator panel.

The following request was modified:

GET / HTTP/2

X-Original-URL:
/admin/delete?username=carlos
The backend executed the administrator action and deleted the user.

The lab was successfully solved.

Why the Attack Worked
The reverse proxy and backend interpreted the request differently.

Reverse Proxy:

GET /
↓

Allowed request.

Backend:

X-Original-URL:
/admin
↓

Returned administrator functionality.

This disagreement created an Access Control Bypass.

Attack Flow
Client
    │
GET /
X-Original-URL: /admin
    │
    ▼
Reverse Proxy

Checks only:

/

↓

Allows

↓

Backend

Reads:

X-Original-URL: /admin

↓

