Key Learning Points
Access control should never rely only on reverse proxies.
Backend applications should never trust client-controlled rewrite headers.
Different application components may interpret the same request differently.
Always investigate how access control is implemented instead of assuming it is secure.
A single access control bypass can often be chained into full administrative compromise.
Pentester's Perspective
Whenever a protected endpoint returns:

401 Unauthorized
or

403 Forbidden
ask the following questions:

Is the restriction implemented by the application or by a reverse proxy?
Does the backend trust any rewrite headers?
Can the request be interpreted differently by different components?
Can URL rewriting bypass access control?
Headers worth testing include:

X-Original-URL
X-Rewrite-URL
The objective is not to memorize specific headers, but to determine whether different parts of the infrastructure interpret the request differently.

